This is what I see when I look in the mirror. No makeup. Wild hair. @candylandhill took this of me last night. I’m completely in my element, happy, content, and exactly, authentically me in this photo. 

A totally big hearted, wild, goofball, not the curated, sexy photos of me, with a team of stylists and makeup artists behind me, taking an hour and half to get me camera ready for those photos. 

My best friend @onthearcfarm and I spoke last night, as we do just about everyday, and she was suggesting I put some more of my most honest real photos on here. She was like “where is my best friend in these photos??” And I had to think about it and go, “you’re right.” 

Although I love being a “bougie bitch” who loves nice things and fancy clothes and getting my hair done, I’m also a wild nature girl, who growing up never wore shoes as I roamed our backyard pond catching frogs, (my sister @katemerrill1 vividly remembers)
had wild hair that was never brushed, unless my mom impatiently would try to brush out my rats nest of a head as I yelped because it had probably been days of not brushing it. Who’s also somewhat neurotic, who generally is very passionate and excited about life, where new adventures both excite me and terrify me, inserts foot in mouth on a daily basis, (and still cringe at things I’ve said or done years ago as I’m in the middle of putting shampoo in my hair while showering). I’m also free, empathetic, deeply compassionate, spiritual, quirky as hell, super curious, adventurous, and really love people. I like to observe people and wonder how they got to being who they are. 

I also get socially anxious and awkward sometimes. Like when I was in high school, when I didn’t have any friends, it felt safer for me to eat my lunch in the locker room by myself. The bathroom was my safe space. Sometimes still today in big social settings, I get anxious and want to run to my safe space. But now I stop myself and sit in the uncomfortable.

I look at myself sometimes and go wow I’m still that same feral, creative kid I once was. Can’t put me in a box. And I love me and it’s taken a long time to embrace all those things about me. So here I am. Wild and free being me.

My heart breaks for Maui, the people, and this beautiful Island. I went to Hawaii for the first time in 2014 (it was on my vision board for years) and had an amazing experience there. The people are so wonderful and it’s such a beautifully epic place. 

I also know what it feels like to lose everything in a fire. I had lost everything I had ever owned in the Malibu fires back in 2018 (losing all of my 20 plus photo albums, family heirlooms from my father and grandparents who passed and so much more.) It was one of the hardest things I had to go through and yet as time went on, and I healed, and years passed by, it ended up being the best thing for me. But I couldn’t have done it without the help of my family, friends, community, and outpouring of love from so many people. My prayer is the same outcome for the people of Lahaina.  I’ve been donating to @sarahshennamaui @ilimanator and personal @gofundme to the people living in Lahaina. Please share or donate to help them rebuild. Link in bio!!!! #mauistrong #lahaina

Everyone: meet Miami Susie in my very early 20s. She was a wild, dramatic, and spicy one. 😂 You’re welcome. 🤣 Been going through old songs I wrote and came across this. 

That one time when I was in my early 20s. I had written and produced this song “Baby you got me” for a boyfriend at the time when he went overseas and was missing him. Had no thoughts on if it would ever be anywhere but needed to express it and sent him this song. And then crazily enough it played on Power96 (the major radio station in Miami) for six months which was cool.

I love you. I am sorry. I am gutted.  So many people are hurting and are in pain. I don’t have the answers, but I do know love is always the way through. I pray for peace. I pray for love. I pray for healing. And I pray for those who are hurting and are gone. And when things feel dark like this, I go back to this quote “Darkness cannot drive out darkness, only light can do that. Hate cannot drive out hate, only love can do
that.”

And I have found in my own life for this to be true. 

We can’t meet pain with more pain, it only causes more suffering. We can only meet it with love. And through love we can heal. Love is the most powerful force of all. Sending love to you all. And I still stand by my quote in my bio, “Love each other, that is all.” 

Gonna be taking a social media break for right now. ♥️👋🏻🫶🏻✨

So this is my before and after pictures. The one on the left was taken several months ago, and the red bathing suit was taken yesterday. I’ve lost 13/14 pounds since the summer. 

I realized I had to change the way I ate because I was addicted to sugar and loved drinking wine a couple times a week.  I was stuck in this cycle where I couldn’t kick the sugar, and my rosacea on my face would get bad immediately after eating sugar or drinking wine. And I felt slower, bigger, like I wasn’t as nimble and my body would break down more, my back would get injured more and I had a lot of inflammation. Also it felt like I had an extra barrier for spiritual protection, but that also doesn’t help me be the best artist because I have to be sensitive, completely open and available, and if I have a physical barrier, I’m blocking my tools and gifts from using them fully. So one day, my sister from another mister @alexandrahealthyliving told me get my blood tests done with @insidetracker and I was shocked where my biomarkers were at. I was on the border for being diabetic and had HIGH cholesterol and lots of inflammation. It was the shock I needed to change things. 

I made a decision because not only were my biomarkers a bit scary to me, but I didn’t like I how I felt nor how I looked, and so I cut the alcohol, the processed sugar and food, cut the bread, and ate and cooked only foods from the earth, (no more processed store boxed food) ate steak, fish, chicken, and then would have veggies like asparagus, artichokes, butternut squash, avocados, salad, and some berries and apples. My rosacea is going away, I don’t get injured as much, and my inflammation is down. I’m feeling so much better. And my biomarkers are back to normal. ❤️

Thank you to @sisustrong my amazing/hilarious trainer who I love to pieces, @bradfeinberg88 and helping me get on track with what I was eating and coaching me (who also got @imaginedragons in ripped shape.) And thank you thank you @inspirewellnessaustralia @karenpykenutrition because you changed my life with changing my diet (what to eat and what not to eat) when I learned about you from @candylandhill a few years ago. Gonna stay on the journey. ✨🥰

I miss you so damn much mom. 💔 For those of you who don’t know, my mom, best friend and soulmate @ly.nne867 passed away suddenly on November 20th a few days before Thanksgiving. It was so raw and came as such a shock to our family that I needed to sit and process it before I shared it here. It’s weird to no longer have any parents as they both have now passed on. 

Instead of planning her usual epic thanksgiving feast, with the best damn homemade stuffing you’ve ever tasted in your life, our family was planning a funeral, and delivering Eulogies. 

She was a force of nature, a YOUNG 75 year old, who was running her usual few miles the days before, and being the life of the party. She was an amazing force of nature, stunningly beautiful, and damn, could she cook-like a Michelin chef. Nothing else ever seems to compare with it. Me and my father loved her cooking so much we would actually lick the plates clean.

She had the most perfect nose, (and no she never got a nose job). She was neurotic, which made her basically an amazing google doctor. And she had a heart of gold. She was so generous, fragile, and yet still so endless tough with so much resilience which is why this comes as such a shock because we all thought she was going to live until she’s one hundred and fifty.

She was so energetic, enthusiastic, positive, and had this big personality yet wanted to leave a small footprint and never wanted to take up too much space. She never wanted to ask for too much. Ever. And she always wanted to please the people she loved around her. She just wanted the people she loved to be happy.

Her message was also so clear to me when she left. We get another day to be here. Another lesson we get to learn. What a gift. She used to say all the time, “Yesterday is history, Tomorrow is a mystery, but Today is a gift. That is why it is called the present.” So I continue to honor her memory and I am doing just that. She lived a full life. And lived her life well. And she would want us to do the same. To not hold onto the past of what life will be without her, but to take her love, lessons, and wisdom into the future. To take her love with us. And I’m doing just that. ❤️
